This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupiers.
The existing movement, which advocates independence from the Netherlands, quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains strict control of the region, not allowing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was formally divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
The city is as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a half-hour flight from Jayapur, the administrative center of the province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour quake on a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city with a population of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses lined with bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs are painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few of the Indonesians arrived here, not to mention the journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
“It was unusual for us to wear this garment,” Degey says, pointing to his bright, woven hand turban, a dark skirt and a bright shirt.
“We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living on the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy levels among the worst in Asia.
But it is also Indonesian gold land.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is only sixty miles from Paniai, a high-altitude province about the size of New Jersey, where 153 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport obtained gold and copper for about $3.1 billion here.
In addition, Papua can boast forest reserves, the value of which is estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, will entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by the New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Demands for greater autonomy from the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden abode and are relentlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and deprived of their liberty.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings of indigenous people in the Papuan highlands in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” the report, published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – especially frequent and pernicious – as stated in another report.
“It’s hard to calculate the number of victims because the incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia, for Human Rights Watch.
Nuts were delayed as Papua resources attracted an influx of immigrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The province’s 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese prawns, "warongs", sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables, served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to withstand the competition.
“Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the indigenous people of Papua,” explains Abeth You, a twenty-four-year-old native of Paniai who moved to Jayapur, the administrative center of the province, because of work.
“Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua – the mother-mama (women) of Papua – have lost their sales market.”
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, popularly known as the Jokovi, vowed to deal with inequality and violations of rights in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former butcher has garnered support from 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But almost nothing has changed in Papua, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for the Jocks, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” Yoo said.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokovi Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out in the street singing Christmas hymns at a caravan in Enarotal when two Indonesian soldiers broke out of the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them that they should turn on the headlights.
According to the local priest Javedt Tebai, one of the soldiers fought their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and witnesses, the soldiers who were drunk were chasing the children and beating them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a government building near the election commission, and the situation worsened the next day.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them the ritual hunting bows and performed the vita, the dance of the Papuan tribe mee pago: they ran around and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation escalated, internal radio soldiers were ordered: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” – that was what he sounded as claimed in the official document, which was seen by the correspondents of the magazine “TIME”.
The fifty-six-year-old Jeremiah Kayame, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, addressing the crowd with a request to walk around the houses.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the wing of his brightly colored wooden house.
Kayame still doesn’t know who fired, but says the bullet came from the sheriffs of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he added.
A local resident, Alfius Yuva, was found three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes told TIME magazine, which, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
“I saw that he was dead...I kissed him.”
General Yotja Mende, the senior inspector of the Papua police, told reporters that his officers were only "protecting" their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” said Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistio in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed, and many more were injured.
The news of the murders reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovi delivered a heartfelt speech in Jayapur, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to deal with the historical abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately, so that it will never happen again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would set up a non-judgmental organization to end historic human rights violations.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
“Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early zeros.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be done,” he said.
Viranto then declined to speak, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through court.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during a bloody vote for East Timor’s independence in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including Pali.
The families of the victims from Paniai encountered such statements with dark distrust.
“In the last three years I have been questioned four times, but there has been absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later, he's still living in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid the military will arrest me, I’m afraid I’ll be shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the people of Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he said.
The shooting didn't stop.
