But locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retaliation,” Domingo Badia, a twenty-nine-year-old man living near the hospital, told TIME magazine.
“I’ve been hiding at home for two days.”
The Deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account, and the mobile police brigade was withdrawn from the region.
Paniai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development is caused by the dissatisfaction of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of the Papuans by arranging sporadic attacks and raids with the kidnapping of Indonesian soldiers.
