EPA Chief Pruitt Refuses to Defer Implement Obama’s Emissions Reduction Rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency canceled his decision to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted by Obama aimed at reducing emissions of air pollutants and smog-producing substances.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that his agency is now more than in previous administrations, listening to the needs of environmental regulators of individual states.
He did not mention the lawsuit against his previous position filed in the Federal Court of Appeals.
The dispute raged around the deadline of October 1, by which the states should ensure compliance with the 2015 ozone-level standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone their compliance for one year to give his department more time to study the plan and to avoid “inconsistency with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who before being appointed by President Trump to his current position as Attorney General of the State of Oklahoma, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental norms.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of norms opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industry.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is yet another legal defeat of the Peuitt course taken in return for the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA had exceeded his powers in an attempt to delay the implementation of the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that, by sharply changing the course on ozone standards, he simply fulfilled the EPA’s obligation to cooperate with states in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“With previous administrations, the EPA often couldn’t settle the deadlines, after which it waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed the deadlines during the settlement of the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous post.
“We don’t believe in legal regulation, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We are also serious about our charter and the power it gives us.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point re-use its “deferral powers and other data under the authority law” to make sure that the “jcyjdfys” standards are on a clear course and on all available information.
Republicans in Congress are insisting on a broader revision of the ozone-related rules.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, aims to postpone implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on this issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that filed lawsuits against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“The EPA’s course changes – after our lawsuits – are an important victory in the struggle for health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog that covers their cities,” Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Man, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia, joined the lawsuit.
Earth-level ozone occurs when ordinary pollutants from machines, power plants, oil processing and chemical plants, and other sources enter the atmosphere in a reaction with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in people who are sensitive to it, resulting in thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health advocates and environmental advocates welcomed the unexpected change in Pruitt’s course.
“It’s hard to think about how much pressure it took to achieve this perfectly logical step from a person who is tasked with protecting the air we breathe,” said Laurie Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
