“We want investigations, we want completions, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he said.
“We can’t move on to healing and reconciliation until justice is achieved.”
The coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the lynching at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI records obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have been at liberty for decades, human rights defenders say the city has always been well-known for two related lynching motives: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a ruling of the Supreme Court for the first time allowed black citizens to vote for the premiership, which was to take place that summer.
Around the same time, according to FBI reports, black user Roger Malcolm struck Barnett Haster, a white landowner, in the fight with a knife — apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that, according to rumors spread in the city, Hester slept with the wife of Malcolm Dorothy, and that the child she was supposed to give birth to was not from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 bail to release Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothea and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove out of prison and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a crowd of lynchmen surrounded the car.
"It seems that Harrison organized and commanded the killings," said one of the FBI's reports.
“It is also obvious that there was a conspiracy between the state and city law enforcement agencies that not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identity of witnesses.”
Brooks calls it shorter.
