New test results to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden have been published
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who have been subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, show that more than 80 percent of those tested were assessed as persons over 18 years of age, but not all trust the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the assessment of age in the asylum process more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) criticised for failing to determine the actual age of some refugees who claimed they were imperfect.
At the moment, the Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were assessed as 18-year-olds or older, and 25 more cases were assessed by the forensic agency as “probably 18-year-olds or older.”
In 432 cases, the finding stated that the person “probably is less than 18.”
Tests are performed only in cases where the age of a person causes doubts.
According to Johan Göransson of the forensic medicine agency, the results correspond to the results of the past months.
"We don't see much difference with the statistics over the past months, the numbers are quite relevant," he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were estimated to have reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers were lying about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases “the fastest, the age of 18 years or more tested.”
However, having looked at 581 published results, the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper found that in 243 cases the person openly stated that he was performing 18 this year.
The method of carrying out a medical age assessment, consisting in making X-rays of wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and x-rayologists, has also provoked criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist at the Claude Marcus Caroline Institute, part of whose work is to assess people’s biological maturity in order to determine whether they have gone through puberty sooner or later than usual.
“I had reasons to think about it, and I don’t think we need to use the measurement methods that are used now.
The biological age is thus determined very inaccurately.
If we can’t identify it with confidence, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told Metro.
However, Göranssen of the forensic medicine agency said in favor of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, it can be said that the risk of mistakenly taking a child as an adult is minor.
We face the greatest risk when a person is soon to be 18, in which case he or she is about 10 percent.”
