How the financial rules of football will affect Neymar's move to Paris
The rules aimed at preventing unrestricted spending by European football clubs do not prevent Neymar’s world record-setting transfer from Spain’s Barcelona to Paris Saint-Germain in France.
Whatever the consequences may be further along the chain, for Paris Saint-Germain by UEFA, the governing body that controls European football, whose authority prohibits teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League tournament.
From the rules of the financial "fire play" introduced by UEFA in 2011, it should be noted that "PSG" will eventually have to show that the transfer of Neymar was financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to free the Brazilian from the contract, and Neymar will receive a complaint that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some financial aspects of Neymar’s move to France.
PSG could certainly be lavish to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team’s funding from the energy-rich ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums of money on the acquisition of players, but they have to balance them at the expense of legitimate sources of income in order to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
FFP introduced Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
A former French footballer believed that clubs that were indebted to huge debts in their quest for success, in essence, were robbing and risking destruction in the event that banks or owners stopped funding.
In 2011, FFP stopped focusing on the debts of the clubs and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model, which was originally used by Roman Abramovich in Chelsea in 2003 – to buy a club with good potential and then to spend seriously in order to improve the team and create a global brand – became a difficult plan.
During the current three-year valuation period, which spans 2018, clubs could suffer losses of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million.
And, despite Platini’s disgraced resignation from the presidency in 2015, his successor to UEFA, Alexander Cheferin, is still determined to curb excessive spending.
“Of course, FFP is alive, and we will, as we move forward, tighten the rules,” Andrea Traverso, who controls FFP at UEFA, told Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay for Neymar’s contract at once, it can allocate this amount for the sake of accountability for the entire duration of his contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer cost can be shown in the annual report as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, more severe sanctions were imposed on PSG, as well as on Abu Dhabi’s Manchester City.
PSG was fined <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>60 million (at that rate it was <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>82 million), which was later reduced to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20 million, and was ordered to limit the composition of its team in the Champions League during the 2014-1015 season by 21 players instead of 25 regulars.
UEFA is tracking clubs that may try to trick its financial inspections by inflating their revenues at the expense of companies associated with the club’s owners.
Even if the Qatari company could promote PSG, but if the amount of funding was considered to exceed the standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the amount of funding from the Department of Tourism of Qatar was inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar’s earnings at PSG could come in the form of payments from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Championship in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will become World Cup ambassador, and such a maneuver could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
The past sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be more closely monitored for any attempts to circumvent the rules.
As reported on Thursday, people familiar with the situation, UEFA did not hold preliminary discussions with PSG about the transfer of Neymar.
They communicated with the Associated Press on conditions of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss the situation of PSG.
