In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its forecasts to an increase of 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on family incomes would continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to about 3% in the fall.
However, the bank warned that rising rates in the next few years would be necessary to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said that borrowing costs would likely have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
The members of the committee also voted in favour of abandoning part of the huge set of economic development measures launched a year ago following Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close its emergency financing plan, under which it provides banks with cheap loans, although it has announced that it now has to provide an additional <0xC2><0xA3>15 billion under this plan – up to <0xC2><0xA3>115 billion.
According to the MPC’s key forecasts, growth in gross domestic product (GDP) will remain slow in the near future, while pressure on real household incomes continues to affect consumption.
On the issue of interest rates, he reiterated that in order to halt inflation, it will require “some tightening of financial policy”, “slightly larger” than markets expect.
At the moment, markets are forecasting the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another one in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases will be “stage” and “limited”.
The bank’s forecasts for an increase this year and the following year are lower than the forecasts made in May, which were 1.9% and 1.7%.
The Bank remained unchanged its forecast of 1.8% in 2018.
After this news, the sterling fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and 0.4% to $1.11.
The decision not to change the rate was made after recent unfortunate growth rates weakened the expectation of an increase; GDP then rose by 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
