The bank’s latest inflation report gave little reason for joy to households, which were hit by high inflation and quite minor wage increases: according to the bank, the pressure will increase before it falls.
The bank added that the financial policy “cannot prevent” the withdrawal from earnings in the next few years, but expects salaries to “significantly” recover by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also geared to growth as a result of rising demand for British goods, due to the low pound rate, which offsets some of the reduced consumer spending.
The decision was made a year after rates were cut to 0.25% last August after the shocking results of a referendum on leaving the European Union, which led to the fall of the pound.
According to the bank, it will likely take four years to have a full impact on prices and the economy.
