Judges offer protection from presidents
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC) commissioned by Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The ICC proposes to limit the powers of the chairpersons of the courts and introduce their election.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the ICTY wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
Its proposals should also be submitted by the Supreme Court within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The ICTY has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the ICTY on behalf of Vladimir Putin from January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with members of the council.
The meeting with the members of the Council on 8 December 2016 discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in the places of detention of citizens (see "H" of 9 December).
As a result of the work of the ICC, there were 25 proposals, which concerned both the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of a judge has successfully passed the contest and received the support of the judicial community, the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the ICC, must submit him to the appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the Chairperson of the right to allocate cases to judges.
To do this, experts allow, a specially written computer program.
Also, the IHR believes that the chairman is not entitled to "pre-determine the results of the qualification certification of the judge, initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments".
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to “the election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and “to grant them powers for a relatively short period of time with a mandatory rotation”.
Now all the presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president at the presentation of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the ICC proposes to reorganize the appeal and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
“It is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts.”
Experts base the practice of arbitral tribunals.
There are “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which guarantee greater independence from regional officials who have difficulty in using the “telephone law”.
The World Court of Justice proposes to strengthen the people’s judges to consider certain “categories of civil and administrative affairs” with their participation.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, rehabilitation at work, protection of honor and dignity, deprivation of driving rights, etc.
“These are just our proposals,” explained the IHR member, a judge of the Constitutional Court in the resignation of Tamar Morshakov.
She also recalled that the president’s mandate was not only for the ICC, but also for the Supreme Court, which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the military (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Human Rights Commissioner in the Russian Federation) to carry out the assignment.
To inform Vladimir Putin about how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev should by September 1.
Living High Life: Half-floor and clever design techniques have turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious home
Joan Lee, a former banker passionate about real estate repairs, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a nice typical house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not collect her things and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Nightsbridge on a much larger area,” Joan says.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price the same day.”
Since the first inspection, the apartment with an area of 1000 square feet has undergone a complete reconstruction.
Originally it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complicated layout – to get into the bedroom, it was necessary to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to squeeze the most out of the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, a lot of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the architectural and design studio Duck & Shed in Notting Hill to use the 12.5-foot-high ceilings to create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would fit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where it could stand in full growth.
Erfan had to think creatively in order to cope with the letter.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We needed to arrange the premises so that they were on top of each other, and we didn’t have to bend.
It was not just necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the premises from above and below.”
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms over each other in a space reserved – and a lot more interesting.
From the half-floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" opens the view of the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with a gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Muja set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror protection panel looks like a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can encircle the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new in the folding kitchen.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding door like a garage.
“Engineering art was involved here,” Erfan will tell about the reinforced steel wood-fibre shield door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it’s very easy to slide.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom, and an improved layout.
“In the end, the floor area is exactly what you’re going to sell, that’s what your property is valued for,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they were able to increase the area of the floors, using quality materials that give the space shades of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the home,” says Erfan.
“No one likes wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This is a testament to the fact that due to a good design and an increased meter, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can choose to stay.
