Is the Islamic State in Libya not defeated by Haftar?
That's not what he was doing.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte was fought by the structures that were subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia the people who carried out this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April of this year, the Libyan delegation was welcomed in the Council of the Federation, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Rosgardia.
You, as we have understood, are in all Libyan regions and you probably imagine the mood of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections reached at the end of July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, the agreements will be broken, the fighting will resume, the parties will try to take power on their own?
For us, a good signal has already been the fact that Saraj and Haftar have agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have reacted extremely negatively to each other.
As for Russia’s position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misurata, and it was on that day Haftar got aboard the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurata they did not believe by coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is precisely to show that we do not only support Haftar, we are in dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar were in touch.
Does the understanding with Russian partners at the human, emotional level facilitate the fact that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know the Russian language?
Russian, if he knows, is very relative.
But what he learned from us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misurata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And that’s why they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they are nostalgic about it.
Do you consider the immediate abolition of the arms embargo against Libya possible?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but as I said before, we are not taking sides in this conflict and would not want to arm one another to the detriment of another.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constantly calls from the Libyans for Russia to somehow contribute to its withdrawal.
The process of drafting the constitution is now being actively promoted in Libya.
We hope that the parties will come up with compromises and reach an internal consensus.
Then the elections will be held, as mentioned at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate authority is finally elected (and now neither party has such a status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be put in the UN Council.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
In recent days, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees floating from Libya, feels left to chance by allies from the EU.
