Michelle Carter Sentencing for Reports That Instigated Conrad Roy's Suicide
A resident of Massachusetts has been sentenced to two and a half years in prison for inciting suicide by texting and phone calls to her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to spend 15 months of her time behind bars and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the unintended murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearings on Thursday: "My family was killed in grief.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at liberty until the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum term of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, shaking her hands and lowering her eyes.
“By her actions she killed Conrad Roy,” the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
"She didn't show remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case that she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her “age, level of maturity, or even mental illness did not noticeably affect her actions.”
The prosecutor read Roy Lynn Roy's mother's statement: "Not a single day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
“I want him to be proud of me and how I do it – I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever,” he said.
Roy's sister, Roy Camdin Roy, said she was relentlessly chasing the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
“To leave the person who has always been with me since I was born is the pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case appears to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for the responsibility for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon dioxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case attracted the attention of the whole country when it became known that it was pushed to the suicide of the Carter message.
“You can hang out, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don’t know there are many ways,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the lighter and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and forbade her to communicate with the press in order not to give her what she wanted.
The views of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British neighbor in an apartment in Italy and was acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Nox published her special opinion in the Los Angeles Times, stating that "Michael Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
