The murder of a journalist emphasizes that in Mexico it is becoming increasingly dangerous.
Employees of the weekly newspaper “Riodos” usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to illuminate the latest violent crimes in the state of Sinaloa related to organized crime, corrupt officials, or the ongoing war.
But today, depressed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: to take children with them to an office where they had already thrown a grenade in 2009, or to leave them at home.
Security experts wrote on the board hanging in the room, three words: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column – evidence is not needed, suspicions and internal feelings will suffice.
These are drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being held in custody by the government or by the cartel, a whole list of assholes that make the work to illuminate chaos in Mexico dangerous.
The violence does not give way, and among the bodies that are multiplying in the country, more and more journalists: according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took his post in December 2012; 589 people have been killed in these cases; 589 people are under threat after attacks.
Among the latter are their publisher and inspiration, co-founder of "Riodose" Javier Valdes Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Waldes wrote in one of his numerous books on violent drug-related crimes.
His absence is felt very acutely, although his presence everywhere - a large photograph of Waldes, showing the middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hangs on the facade of the building "Riodose" of the physics; two of the physics of the physics of the physics of the physics; two of the reporters in 30 years, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Fmirez.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss his general injury, his nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor’s office was organized for the investigation of journalistic affairs in 2010, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders perpetrated each year related to drug trafficking and organized crime, killers of journalists rarely appear in court.
Reporters at Riodos insist they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, though they are killed with grief, although it is far more dangerous now.
“Without information about the killers, without justice from security talks at meetings, there is little use,” says Ibarra.
“It’s very foolish to spend time at this seminar,” he says.
“Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone.”
On the morning of May 15, Valdes left the office of "Riodos" in the capital of the state of Culiacan.
He only managed to walk a couple of blocks before his red Toyota King was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper - which means "Twelfth River."
The shooter got off his car and smashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually quickly dissipate around the Kuliakan.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdez.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the United States in January last year, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlefields in the country as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum formed.
Let’s not talk about the fact that one or more people are killed every day in the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with two-story mausoleums of narcotics, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let’s forget for a minute that the state of “rest” is just when one of the cartels takes control of a coastal state with important ports and routes of drug trafficking leading to the United States.
Despite the fact that Valdes was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorkes, a 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, was crushed by guilt for not being able to protect a friend.
He thinks the murder was helped by two mistakes.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is fighting the sons of Guzman.
The publication could have angered the sons; people who were supposedly members of the gang bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Waldes to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper was seized, which wrote about the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was regarded as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been out of danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would be forever.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroeste and in 2003, together with five colleagues, founded Riodos, selling his $50 stock.
In Sinaloa “it was impossible to engage in journalism without affecting the topic of drugs,” Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for bold and honest publishing, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this publication they could read about something that no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after her founding, Riodos received the prestigious Maria Murs Cabo Award for her work as a reporter in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his bravery in investigating the drug trade in Mexico, wherever it led.
He admitted frankly that he was scared.
“I want to live on,” he said at the CPJ award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa - "it's a way of life," he said in an interview with Rompeviento TV in October last year.
“You have to take on the tasks that lie on you as a journalist – either that way or you’re just hitting a fool.”
I don't want to be asked, "What were you doing when there were so many deaths around... why didn't you tell me what was going on?"
The staff of the "Riodos" miss Valdes, a joker, who quarreled, like a loader in the port, a friend, generous on hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to snuggle alive.
They depended on the order they had set.
He always had to wear his hat.
He was supposed to go to El Guayabo, the bar in front of the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: Has his love for a once-established order destroyed him?
His death caused them to doubt their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you get along with their wives, their children, their legal business, and their underground drug transport airports.
"These things were on the line," Bohorkes said.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to believe your instincts.
