Create a novel-comic: A castle in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a port for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the Bull River Valley in Kent County, he watched a tumultuous history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with a dry hair and a tendency to historical documents, for a comic novel.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he said.
“You feel it so personal when you hold this letter in your hand.”
"The Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about the families who lived in Scotland; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac G. Lenkevich, Brian May Smith, William Axley, Beckley.
This is not the first book by Rhodes, which is based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote "Tooths of a Dead Man and Other Stories" - a collection of documents from the British Library; this project unexpectedly touched him to the depths of his soul.
“I could just scratch a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent who worked on the Jacobites,” he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those times a fire was lit for lighting.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there too.
Oh, how I love the archives!"
For a person who has such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months ("Honestly, I've been a little bit over there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the “new” Victorian castle, walking through the archives, and looking at the many treasures of the mansion and old things – for example, hyenas on the walls or bottles that have been lying in the rubble for centuries.
He walked around the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to woodworkers, gardeners, and sometimes artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drinked the whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scottney Castle is not much studied, because the National Fund was given full access to it only in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhodes arrived there ten years later, the staff had only just begun to deal with the archive, which he described as “what the aristocrats had fallen to the attic for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think land disputes are boring,” says Rhodes, “but there were two families fighting for this birch.
That's the way it is, guys!"
In some of the history of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider explorations in English history: for example, in "The Worker", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the peasant revolution of 1381.
"There is information about the rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex," Rods says.
“The peasant uprising started in these places, and I thought the uprising was the right start.
Maybe they were connected?”
Other plots are closely related to the castle's history - for example, "The Priest", which tells of a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or “The Smuggler,” about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own burials, filling the tomb with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the tomb was excavated).
Darrells are the favourite family of Rhodes from all that Scottney lived in: “The Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect scoundrel, forever in debt and spent money on things they couldn’t afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women – I imagine them as a company of nice guys who know how to care for the heirs of the great estate.
After finishing work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish deafness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Eliamyamyaki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it grew again into a forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he said.
“I felt like, ‘Fuck you, I have to get back to real life again.’”
