Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help alleviate COPD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies say the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those who suffer from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestines ensure that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells that are able to trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body, and at the same time do not harm sensitive tissues.
If the equilibrium is too much violated in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan — one of the building blocks of protein — to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is part of a normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in the mice’s diet, the more these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan may contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation in the intestines.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Servantes-Barraganvas, studying the variety of immune cells that increase tolerance, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line but was not contained separately.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by mouse gut microbiomes — communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice’s gut cells was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were detected in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that didn’t have them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment who did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the fluid — without bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
Immune cells have been transformed into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice’s diet, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was reduced by twice, the number of cells also dropped by twice.
Dr. Servantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerating cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as well as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
She says, "Perhaps we need to intensify the development of these cells, because inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an increase in their population.”
