A British inventor invented a microchip to get into a house and a car by swinging his hand.
The British inventor became the first person in the country to install a microchip so that he could open the door of his home, enter the office and even drive a car with a simple handshake.
Thirty-three-year-old Stephen Northam has made a tiny chip between his big and index fingers and now through his company BioTech offers this service to companies and individuals who want to simplify their lives through technology.
He teamed up with Dr. Jeff Watson, an anesthesiologist consultant from the Royal University of Winchester, to ensure that the application procedure was conducted in accordance with medical standards.
The technology is similar to a microchip that is fed to cats and dogs, and the procedure takes only 30 seconds.
The company also replaces locks in homes and cars with chip-compatible locks at a price of <0xC2><0xA3>300 per lock.
The married father of one child has already installed the technology in his home and in his car "BMW Z4", which is manufactured when his hand is on the steering wheel.
The requisite for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the records of the armed forces, provided to the magazine «TIME», the decision of the White House last month to squeeze the helicopter of the Marine Corps into the South Lawn at an event dedicated to American industrial production, cost taxpayers as much as 24,000 to.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as “Marine One” when the president is on board, became the central element of the July 17 White House event where U.S. construction programs were demonstrated.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and top White House officials have inspected technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, made in Connecticut, was on display next to a yacht from the state of Man, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a truckloader from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for the management of the helicopter, the Military Administration of the White House ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO" aircraft, only 36 hours before the helicopter arrived.
“I just wanted you to make sure that you were aware because this is an unusual event that is widely discussed in the press,” the commander of the HMX-1 wrote in an e-mail to his boss, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn around 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and will remain there until the lawn is released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with working hours restrictions.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was required in the end.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal officials from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has clarified whether the measure is contrary to this decision.
"We asked if this was a violation of Hatch's law, and we said no," the commander wrote.
“You don’t seem to be going anywhere,” the deputy chief replied.
The "Made in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event, and the Hatcha law did not apply to it.
But even the official events have a political note.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance the health care reform that was in development at the time in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government decrees.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
The presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to ask them only in the interest of photoopportunity is unusual.
Trump had already been the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane ran in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about the use of the presidential plane in front of him.
“The White House is thrilled with the show Made in America, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
The HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the Southern lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with accuracy up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 held 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight, made for the event "Made in America", was calculated for the crew at the expense of the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of the “non-presidential task of providing support.”
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
The representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South lawn.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of Defense for the 2017 fiscal year, the rate of compensation of the Ministry of Defense for the VH-3D is 24,380 US dollars per hour of flight.
The records of the unit recorded that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield based on the air base of the Quantico Marine Corps in Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using the helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“It’s completely wrong to calculate the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement,” says Walters.
“These approximate rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocations.”
According to a study carried out in 2015 by the REND Corporation, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of the personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of the fuel, the service and the costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was in favour of using the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate the things that were done in America this week,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, which so many Americans have worked tirelessly on.
Therefore, of course, it is quite appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump was interacting with the helicopter while inspecting the South lawn during the event, but he was definitely in the driver’s seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump turned to representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press on the subject of his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said. “I have three of them.”
Moscow to allocate grants for resuscitation departments of urban hospitals
Each year, "Saving Life" grants will be awarded to resuscitations and intensive care departments of the capital clinics.
The funds will be used to encourage doctors and nurses.
The mayor of Moscow Sergey Sobyanin visited the City Clinical Hospital named Judena.
During the examination of the clinic, he handed over a thank-you letter to the doctor-traumatologist-orthopedist Viktor Protsko, under the guidance of which the most complex operation to reconstruct the foot of a teenager was carried out.
Sergey Sobyanin also told about the decision to award grants annually to the rehabilitation and intensive care departments of urban clinics.
The funds will be directed to the encouragement of doctors and nurses.
According to the mayor, the Yudina Clinical Hospital is one of the largest in Moscow to date.
In recent years, the clinic has received new modern equipment, allowing its doctors to perform unique operations.
The clinic was opened in 1961 on the basis of the Kolomen Rural Hospital.
Currently, the departments of the medical institution are designed for the reception of more than a thousand patients.
In addition to resuscitation and hospital, there are daycare facilities here.
The staff of the hospital has 2,800 people.
The total area of the clinic is 23.7 hectares.
In February of this year, the medical institution became a participant in a pilot project on the organization of short-term hospitals (SCP).
They are designed to carry out relatively small operations.
In the process of surgical interventions, advanced medical equipment is used, which allows to significantly reduce the time of rehabilitation of patients.
After the surgery, they only spend a few hours in the hospital.
In the first half of this year alone, 36,000 patients were hospitalized at the Yudin Clinical Hospital.
Medical staff of the clinic performed 15,800 surgeries of varying degrees of complexity.
