Democracy in Afghanistan depends on the role of women in politics, the UN said.
The elections can only be representative if they are attended by all members of society, including women, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
According to Nikolas Haysom, the current head of the United Nations Assistance Mission to Afghanistan, hundreds of women are running for provincial council elections, three women are fighting for the post of vice president, and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
“The role of women cannot be overestimated,” he said in a statement on Wednesday.
The choice can be fully representative only when women are fully involved in them and included in all stages of the electoral process.
Elections to the provincial councils and presidential elections will be held in Afghanistan on April 5.
The Taliban is threatening to disrupt the election process, which coincides with the transition of international forces from combat operations to the role of advisers.
In this year’s election, power is transitioning peacefully from one democratically elected government to another for the first time.
Haysom said that increasing the role of women would contribute to the success of democracy in Afghanistan.
According to the Independent Electoral Commission of Afghanistan, out of a total of 3.6 million registered voters, 1.2 million are women.
